<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1895-04-26T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1895-04-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="351" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d351">
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Gresham</persName> to Sir
                                    <persName type="to">Julian Pauncefote</persName>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State.</hi><lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1895-04-26"><hi rend="italic">April 26,
                                1895</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 88.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Excellency</hi>: I have the honor, in connection
                            with my note of the 18th instant concerning the proposed restrictions
                            upon the traffic in <pb facs="0419" n="1153" xml:id="pg_1153"/> arms and
                            ammunition in Samoa, to inclose for your information a copy of a note
                            addressed to the German ambassador on the 25th instant,<note n="1" xml:id="d351fn1">See <ref target="#pg_1136">p. 1136</ref>.</note> in
                            relation to the reported endeavors of the municipal council at Apia “by
                            the issuance of supplementary orders to restrict the right of search,”
                            provided for by the ordinance of August 14, 1894.</p>
                        <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed><hi rend="smallcaps">W. Q. Gresham</hi>.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>